    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Shortest distance between lines (x-3)/3 = (y-8)/-1 = (z-3)/1 and (x+3)/-3 = (y+7)/2 = (z-6)/4:</text>
            <option id="A">3 sqrt(30)</option><option id="B">sqrt(270)</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">All are correct</option>
            <answer>D</answer><explanation>Standard SD formula using cross product of directions (-6, -15, 3). SD = |(6, 15, -3).(6, 15, -3)| / sqrt(270) = 270/sqrt(270) = sqrt(270) = 3 sqrt(30).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Equation of plane passing through intersection of x+y+z=1 and 2x+3y-z+4=0 and parallel to x-axis:</text>
            <option id="A">y - 3z + 6 = 0</option><option id="B">x + y + z = 1</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Plane: (1+2k)x + (1+3k)y + (1-k)z + (4k-1) = 0. Parallel to x-axis means 1+2k=0 -&gt; k=-1/2. Substitue k.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Foot of perpendicular from origin to x+2y-2z=9 is:</text>
            <option id="A">(1, 2, -2)</option><option id="B">(0, 0, 0)</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Line: x/1 = y/2 = z/-2 = k. Into plane: k + 4k + 4k = 9 -&gt; 9k=9 -&gt; k=1. Point (1, 2, -2).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Direction cosines of two lines satisfying l+m+n=0 and l^2+m^2-n^2=0 are:</text>
            <option id="A">(-1/sqrt(6), 2/sqrt(6), -1/sqrt(6)) and (2/sqrt(6), -1/sqrt(6), -1/sqrt(6))</option><option id="B">None</option><option id="C">C</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Solve n = -(l+m) -&gt; l^2+m^2-(l+m)^2 = 0 -&gt; -2lm = 0. Either l=0 or m=0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Image of point (1, 3, 4) in plane 2x - y + z + 3 = 0 is:</text>
            <option id="A">(-3, 5, 2)</option><option id="B">(0, 0, 0)</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Use formula (x-x1)/A = (y-y1)/B = (z-z1)/C = -2(Ax1+By1+Cz1+D)/(A^2+B^2+C^2). -2(2-3+4+3)/6 = -2(6)/6 = -2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Distance of (1, -2, 3) from plane x-y+z=5 measured parallel to line x/2 = y/3 = z/-6:</text>
            <option id="A">1 unit</option><option id="B">7 units</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Line through (1,-2,3): x=1+2k, y=-2+3k, z=3-6k. Into plane: (1+2k) - (-2+3k) + (3-6k) = 5 -&gt; 6-7k = 5 -&gt; k = 1/7. Distance = |k| * sqrt(4+9+36) = 1/7 * 7 = 1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Equation of plane containing lines x-5 = (y-7)/4 = z+3 and (x-8)/7 = y-4 = (z-5)/3:</text>
            <option id="A">x - y + z = -5? No, check coplanarity.</option><option id="B">Coplanar check required</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>B</answer><explanation>Lines are coplanar if [(a2-a1) b1 b2] = 0. Use determinant.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Angle between line joins (x1,y1,z1), (0,0,0) and z-axis is alpha. Then tan^2 alpha = :</text>
            <option id="A">(x1^2 + y1^2) / z1^2</option><option id="B">z1^2 / (x1^2+y1^2)</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>cos^2 alpha = z1^2 / (x1^2+y1^2+z1^2). sec^2 alpha = (x1^2+y1^2+z1^2)/z1^2. tan^2 alpha = sec^2 - 1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A plane through (2,3,4) is perpendicular to line joining origin and (2,3,4). Its equation is:</text>
